        </figure>
    </introduction>

    <subsection>
        <title>Difference of Squares</title>

        <p>Let's factor <m>x^2-16</m>. In general, a trinomial looks like <m>ax^2+bx+c</m>. For <m>x^2-16</m>, the second term is missing. We could treat the binomial <m>x^2-16</m> as a trinomial: <m>x^2+0x-16</m>. To factor this trinomial, we will list <m>-16</m>'s factor pairs, and try to find a pair whose sum is <m>0</m>:</p>

        <table>
            <caption>Factor Pairs of <m>-16</m></caption>
            <tabular>
                <col halign="center"/>
                <col halign="center"/>
                <col halign="center"/>
                <col halign="center"/>
                <row bottom="medium">
                    <cell>Factor Pairs</cell>
                    <cell>Sum</cell>
                    <cell>Factor Pairs</cell>
                    <cell>Sum</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>1\cdot(-16)</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>-15</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>(-1)\cdot16</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>15</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>2\cdot(-8)</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>-6</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>(-2)\cdot8</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>6</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                    <cell>n/a</cell>
                    <cell/>
                    <cell/>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>4\cdot(-4)</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                    <cell>...</cell>
                    <cell>...</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>

        <p>The sum of <m>4</m> and <m>-4</m> is <m>0</m>, so the solution is<me>x^2-16=(x+4)(x-4)</me>We can find a pair of factors whose sum is <m>0</m>, because <m>16</m> happens to be a square number. We can similarly find <m>5</m> and <m>-5</m> for <m>-25</m>, <m>6</m> and <m>-6</m> for <m>-36</m>, etc. In general, we can factor <m>x^2-y</m> as long as <m>y</m> is a square number. We can summarize a formula, called the <term>Difference of Squares</term> formula<me>a^2-b^2=(a+b)(a-b)</me>Let's factor <m>x^2-16</m> with the formula:<md>
            <mrow>\amp a^2-b^2=(a+b)(a-b)</mrow>
            <mrow>x^2-16=\amp x^2-4^2=(x+4)(x-4)</mrow>
        </md>In this problem, <m>x</m> corresponds to <m>a</m> in the formula, and <m>4</m> corresponds to <m>b</m>.</p>

        <remark><p>It's a common mistake to do <m>x^2+16=(x+4)(x-4)</m>. The binomial <m>x^2+16</m> is actually prime.</p></remark>

        <p>To use this formula, it's important to recognize the following square numbers<me>1, 4, 9, 16, 25, 36, 49, 64, 81, 100, 121, 144</me>Let's look at a few more examples.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Factor the following binomials.<md>
                    <mrow>a)\text{  } \amp p^2-1</mrow>
                    <mrow>b)\text{  } \amp 1-p^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>c)\text{  } \amp m^2n^2-4</mrow>
                    <mrow>d)\text{  } \amp 4z^2-9</mrow>
                    <mrow>e)\text{  } \amp 9k^2-64l^2</mrow>
                </md></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><md>
                    <mrow>\amp a)\text{  }p^2-1=(p)^2-(1)^2=(p+1)(p-1)</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp b)\text{  }1-p^2=(1)^2-(p)^2=(1-p)(1+p)</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp c)\text{  }m^2n^2-4=(mn)^2-(2)^2=(mn+2)(mn-2)</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp d)\text{  }4z^2-9=(2z)^2-(3)^2=(2z+3)(2z-3)</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp e)\text{  }9k^2-64l^2=(3k)^2-(8l)^2=(3k+8l)(3k-8l)</mrow>
                </md></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Factor the following binomials.<md>
                    <mrow>a)\text{  } \amp x^4-9</mrow>
                    <mrow>b)\text{  } \amp 4y^4-9x^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>c)\text{  } \amp m^6-n^8</mrow>
                    <mrow>d)\text{  } \amp p^4-1</mrow>
                    <mrow>e)\text{  } \amp 9q^2-2</mrow>
                    <mrow>f)\text{  } \amp x^2+1</mrow>
                </md></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><md>
                    <mrow>a)\text{  } \amp x^4-9=(x^2)^2-(3)^2=(x^2+3)(x^2-3)</mrow>
                    <mrow>b)\text{  } \amp 4y^4-9x^2=(2y^2)^2-(3x)^2=(2y^2+3x)(2y^2-3x)</mrow>
                    <mrow>c)\text{  } \amp m^6-n^8=(m^3)^2-(n^4)^2=(m^3+n^4)(m^3-n^4)</mrow>
                    <mrow>d)\text{  } \amp p^4-1=(p^2)-(1)^2=(p^2+1)(p^2-1)=(p^2+1)(p+1)(p-1)</mrow>
                    <mrow>e)\text{  } \amp 9q^2-2\text{ is prime.}</mrow>
                    <mrow>f)\text{  } \amp x^2+1\text{ is prime.}</mrow>
                </md></p>

                <p>Notice that for Problem d, we cannot stop at <m>(p^2+1)(p^2-1)</m> because <m>(p^2-1)</m> can be further factored into <m>(p+1)(p-1)</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>No matter what formulas we will use, we should always try to factor out the common factor if possible. Compare the following:<md>
            <mrow>x^2-4x\amp=x(x-4)</mrow>
            <mrow>x^2-4\amp=(x+2)(x-2)</mrow>
        </md>In the next few examples, factor out the common factor if possible, and then use the difference of squares formula.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Factor the following binomials.<md>
                    <mrow>a)\text{  } \amp 2p^2-2</mrow>
                    <mrow>b)\text{  } \amp m^2n^4-4n^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>c)\text{  } \amp 12z^3-27z</mrow>
                </md></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><md>
                    <mrow>a)\text{  } \amp 2p^2-2=2(p^2-1)=2(p+1)(p-1)</mrow>
                    <mrow>b)\text{  } \amp m^2n^4-4n^2=n^2(m^2n^2-4)=n^2(mn+2)(mn-2)</mrow>
                    <mrow>c)\text{  } \amp 12z^3-27z=3z(4z^2-9)=3z(2z+3)(2z-3)</mrow>
                </md></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <remark><p>Note that we could use the Listing Factor Pairs Method, AC Method and Generic Rectangles Method to factor those problems, but the Difference of Squares Formula saves time.</p></remark>

    </subsection>

