    <subsection>
        <title>Perfect Squares</title>

        <p>Let's multiply <m>(a+b)^2</m>:<md>
            <mrow>(a+b)^2\amp=(a+b)(a+b)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=a(a+b)+b(a+b)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=a^2+ab+ab+b^2</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=a^2+2ab+b^2</mrow>
        </md></p>

        <p>This implies a trinomial in the form of <m>a^2+2ab+b^2</m> can be factored to <m>(a+b)^2</m>. We call it the <term>Perfect Square Formula</term>:<me>a^2+2ab+b^2=(a+b)^2</me>When we use this formula to factor trinomials, the difficult part is to determine whether a trinomial is in the form of <m>a^2+2ab+b^2</m>. For example, does the trinomial <m>x^2+6x+9</m> match <m>a^2+2ab+b^2</m>?</p>

        <p>In <m>x^2+6x+9</m>, it's obvious <m>x</m> matches <m>a</m> in <m>a^2+2ab+b^2</m>.</p>

        <p>It's important to recognize that <m>9</m> is a square number, which can be writen as <m>3^2</m>. This implies <m>3</m> matches <m>b</m> in <m>a^2+2ab+b^2</m>.</p>

        <p>The key step is to see whether <m>6x</m> in <m>x^2+6x+9</m> matches <m>2ab</m> in <m>a^2+2ab+b^2</m>. Since we have matched <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> with <m>x</m> and <m>3</m>, <m>2ab</m> would be <m>2(x)(3)=6x</m>, which happens to match the second term in <m>x^2+6x+9</m>.</p>

        <p>Since all three terms in <m>x^2+6x+9</m> matches <m>a^2+2ab+b^2</m>, we can use the perfect square formula to factor:<md>
            <mrow>a^2+2ab+b^2\amp=(a+b)^2</mrow>
            <mrow>x^2+6x+9=(x)^2+2(x)(3)+(3)^2\amp=(x+3)^2</mrow>
        </md>A second perfect square formula is<me>a^2-2ab+b^2=(a-b)^2</me>We can combine those two formulas into one:<me>a^2\pm2ab+b^2=(a\pm b)^2</me>Let's look at a few examples.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Factor <m>4x^2-20xy+25y^2</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>The square numbers <m>4</m> and <m>25</m> give us the hint that we could use the perfect square formula <m>a^2-2ab+b^2=(a-b)^2</m>. We will try to use the formula to factor.</p>

                <p>Since <m>4x^2=(2x)^2</m>, <m>2x</m> matches <m>a</m> in <m>a^2-2ab+b^2=(a-b)^2</m>.</p>

                <p>Since <m>25y^2=(5y)^2</m>, <m>5y</m> matches <m>b</m> in <m>a^2-2ab+b^2=(a-b)^2</m>.</p>

                <p>If <m>a=2x</m> and <m>b=5y</m>, <m>2ab=2(2x)(5y)=20xy</m>, which happens to match the second term in <m>4x^2-20xy+25y^2</m>.</p>

                <p>Finally, we can use the perfect square formula to factor the given trinomial:<md>
                    <mrow>4x^2-20xy+25y^2\amp=(2x)^2-2(2x)(5y)+(5y)^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=(2x-5y)^2</mrow>
                </md></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Factor <m>32x^6y^2-48x^5y+18x^4</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>The first step of factoring any polynomial is to factor out the common factor if possible. For this trinomial, the common factor is <m>2x^4</m>, so we do <m>32x^6y^2-48x^5y+18x^4=2x^4(16x^2y^2-24xy+9)</m>.</p>

                <p>The square numbers <m>16</m> and <m>9</m> in <m>16x^2y^2-24xy+9</m> give us the hint that we could use the perfect square formula <m>a^2-2ab+b^2=(a-b)^2</m>. We will try to use the formula to factor.</p>

                <p>Since <m>16x^2y^2=(4xy)^2</m>, <m>4xy</m> matches <m>a</m> in <m>a^2-2ab+b^2=(a-b)^2</m>.</p>

                <p>Since <m>9=(3)^2</m>, <m>3</m> matches <m>b</m> in <m>a^2-2ab+b^2=(a-b)^2</m>.</p>

                <p>If <m>a=4xy</m> and <m>b=3</m>, <m>2ab=2(4xy)(3)=24xy</m>, which happens to match the second term in <m>16x^2y^2-24xy+9</m>.</p>

                <p>Finally, we can use the perfect square formula to further factor the trinomial:<md>
                    <mrow>32x^6y^2-48x^5y+18x^4\amp=2x^4(16x^2y^2-24xy+9)</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=2x^4[(4xy)^2-2(4xy)(3)+(3)^2]</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=2x^4(4xy-3)^2</mrow>
                </md></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <remark><p>Note that we could use the Listing Factor Pairs Method, AC Method and Generic Rectangles Method to factor those problems, but the Perfect Squares Formula saves time.</p></remark>

    </subsection>

