    <subsection>
        <title>Sum/Difference of Cubes Formulas</title>

        <p>We will learn two <term>Sum/Difference of Cubes Formulas</term>:<md>
            <mrow>a^3+b^3\amp=(a+b)(a^2-ab+b^2)</mrow>
            <mrow>a^3-b^3\amp=(a-b)(a^2+ab+b^2)</mrow>
            </md>They can be combined into one formula:<me>a^3\pm b^3=(a\pm b)(a^2\mp ab+b^2)</me>
        </p>

        <p>We need to recognize square numbers when we try to use the Difference of Squares Formula <m>a^2-b^2=(a+b)(a-b)</m>. Similarly, when we try to use the Sum/Difference of Cubes Formula, we need to be able to recognize the first few cubic numbers:<md>
            <mrow>1^3\amp=1</mrow>
            <mrow>2^3\amp=8</mrow>
            <mrow>3^3\amp=27</mrow>
            <mrow>4^3\amp=64</mrow>
            <mrow>5^3\amp=125</mrow>
        </md></p>

        <p>Let's look at a few exampels.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Factor <m>x^3-27</m>.</p>

                <p>We recognize that <m>x^3=(x)^3</m> and <m>27=(3)^3</m>, so we can use the Difference of Cubes Formula to factor the binomial:<md>
                    <mrow>x^3-27\amp=(x)^3-(3)^3</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=(x-3)[(x)^2+(x)(3)+(3)^2]</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=(x-3)(x^2+3x+9)</mrow>
                </md></p>

                <p>In the second step, we substituted <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> in the formula with <m>x</m> and <m>3</m>:<md>
                    <mrow>(a^3-b^3)\amp=(a-b)(a^2+ab+b^2)</mrow>
                    <mrow>(x)^3-(3)^3\amp=(x-3)[(x)^2+(x)(3)+(3)^2]</mrow>
                </md></p>
            </statement>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Factor <m>y^3+1</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>We recognize that <m>y^3=(y)^3</m> and <m>1=(1)^3</m>, so we can use the Sum of Cubes Formula to factor the binomial:<md>
                    <mrow>y^3+1\amp=(y)^3+(1)^3</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=(y+1)[(y)^2-(y)(1)+(1)^2]</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=(y+1)(y^2-y+1)</mrow>
                </md></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Factor <m>27m^3-64n^3</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>We recognize that <m>27m^3=(3m)^3</m> and <m>64n^3=(4n)^3</m>, so we can use the Difference of Cubes Formula to factor the binomial:<md>
                    <mrow>27m^3-64n^3\amp=(3m)^3-(4n)^3</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=(3m-4n)[(3m)^2-(3m)(4n)+(4n)^2]</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=(3m-4n)(9m^2-12mn+16n^2)</mrow>
                </md></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Factor <m>3x^3-3</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>As the first step of factoring, we always try to factor out the common factor. In this problem, we will factor out the common factor <m>3</m>, and then use Difference of Cubes Formula.<md>
                    <mrow>3x^3-27\amp=3(x^3-1)</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=3[(x)^3-(1)^3]</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=3(x-1)[(x)^2+(x)(1)+(1)^2]</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=3(x-1)(x^2+x+1)</mrow>
                </md></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

    </subsection>

